{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"language":"python","display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.12","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"nvidiaTeslaT4","dataSources":[{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":13973040,"datasetId":8908164,"databundleVersionId":14747316},{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":15432655,"datasetId":9705758,"databundleVersionId":16351808}],"dockerImageVersionId":31287,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":true}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Person Search on PRW Dataset\n## Machine Learning for Computer Vision, University of Bologna, A.Y. 2025-2026\n\n|       |      |\n|-------|-------|\n| **Full Name** | `Luwam Major Kefali` |\n| **Email** | `luwammajor.kefali@studio.unibo.it` |\n\n**Task:** Implement a Person Search model (joint pedestrian detection + person re-identification) on the PRW dataset.\n\n**Platform:** Kaggle, 2x T4 GPUs. Training runs via `torchrun` with DistributedDataParallel.\n\n**How to run:** Set `TRAINING_MODE = False` to skip training and load pre-trained weights for evaluation. Set `True` to retrain via DDP (approximately 2 hours on 2x T4). ","metadata":{"_uuid":"cfdcae7f-b561-41d5-b8d9-bc30a88b1b0d","_cell_guid":"7bd2b0d1-8754-4891-aa04-30a90c6c61c4","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 1. Introduction\n\nPerson Search combines pedestrian detection and person re-identification into a single end-to-end pipeline. Unlike classical Re-ID, where bounding boxes are given by a perfect detector, Person Search operates on raw scene images. The model must locate all persons and identify the target simultaneously, which makes it closer to a real surveillance scenario, for example finding a missing person in a crowded area (Zheng et al., CVPR 2017).\n\nThe main advantage of an end-to-end approach over a two-stage pipeline (detect, then re-identify separately) is that the backbone features are shared. The detector and the Re-ID branch can co-adapt: the backbone learns representations that are good for both localization and discrimination. Errors from the detector no longer propagate blindly to the Re-ID module since the two tasks are trained jointly (Xiao et al., CVPR 2017).\n\nIn this project I build an end-to-end model based on Faster R-CNN with an added Re-ID head trained using OIM loss (Online Instance Matching). I run two ablation studies to verify the design choices: swapping ResNet-50 for ResNet-18 (testing backbone capacity), and replacing OIM with batch-hard triplet loss (testing the Re-ID objective).\n\nTraining uses DistributedDataParallel across 2 T4 GPUs (Kaggle), with Weights & Biases for experiment tracking.","metadata":{"_uuid":"1e0f0b02-363b-45ec-bea6-61291c33c449","_cell_guid":"1aceeaa7-7702-425d-91d9-f55379bf82a7","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import shutil, glob, os\n\n# correct paths for this Kaggle environment\nSCRIPTS_DIR = \"/kaggle/input/datasets/luwammajor/prw-person-search-scripts\"\nDATASET_ROOT = \"/kaggle/input/datasets/edoardomerli/prw-person-re-identification-in-the-wild\"\n\n# copy scripts to working directory\nfor f in glob.glob(os.path.join(SCRIPTS_DIR, \"*.py\")):\n    shutil.copy(f, \".\")\n\nprint(\"Copied:\", [f for f in os.listdir(\".\") if f.endswith(\".py\")])","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-29T21:57:39.074255Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-29T21:57:39.074571Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-29T21:57:39.118589Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-29T21:57:39.074531Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-29T21:57:39.117795Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Copied: ['train_ddp.py', 'models.py', 'losses.py', 'eval_utils.py', 'dataset.py']\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":1},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# install packages\nimport subprocess, sys\nfor p in [\"scipy\", \"scikit-learn\", \"matplotlib\", \"tqdm\", \"wandb\"]:\n    subprocess.run([sys.executable, \"-m\", \"pip\", \"install\", \"-q\", p], check=False)\nprint(\"Setup complete\")","metadata":{"_uuid":"e260ba7d-c6b7-48b2-8922-3051725be9f1","_cell_guid":"cf6aa61c-4205-41d0-bb21-5bb9c6f44862","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false},"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-29T21:57:44.784242Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-29T21:57:44.785012Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-29T21:58:03.178338Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-29T21:57:44.784971Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-29T21:58:03.177304Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Setup complete\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":2},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import os, os.path as osp, random, warnings\nimport numpy as np\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport matplotlib.patches as patches\nfrom PIL import Image\nfrom collections import Counter\n\nimport torch\nimport torchvision\nimport torchvision.transforms as T\n\n# our modules \nfrom dataset import PRWGalleryDataset, PRWQueryDataset\nfrom models import build_model\nfrom eval_utils import (extract_gallery_features, extract_query_features,\n                        eval_search_prw, collate_fn)\n\nwarnings.filterwarnings(\"ignore\")\ntorch.manual_seed(42)\nrandom.seed(42)\nnp.random.seed(42)\n\nDEVICE = torch.device(\"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\")\nprint(f\"Device: {DEVICE}\")\nprint(f\"GPUs available: {torch.cuda.device_count()}\")\nprint(f\"PyTorch {torch.__version__}, torchvision {torchvision.__version__}\")\n\n# config\nTRAINING_MODE   = True\nREID_DIM        = 256\nNUM_TRAIN_PIDS  = 482\nDET_THRESH      = 0.5\nDATASET_ROOT    = None   # set after donwload","metadata":{"_uuid":"f5b902f3-6998-49d2-a50d-43f35cf9ca73","_cell_guid":"83128489-39fa-4c73-81f2-d461a6975c18","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false},"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-29T22:00:28.382306Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-29T22:00:28.383046Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-29T22:00:37.848478Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-29T22:00:28.383010Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-29T22:00:37.847228Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Device: cuda\nGPUs available: 2\nPyTorch 2.9.0+cu126, torchvision 0.24.0+cu126\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":3},{"cell_type":"code","source":"DATASET_ROOT = \"/kaggle/input/datasets/edoardomerli/prw-person-re-identification-in-the-wild\"\nprint(f\"PRW root: {DATASET_ROOT}\")\nprint(\"Contents:\", sorted(os.listdir(DATASET_ROOT)))","metadata":{"_uuid":"7661ef38-73a4-4915-81b0-b3d5e368c2dd","_cell_guid":"e04e0345-a618-408d-9c29-015c03ab9e31","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false},"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-29T22:00:44.121782Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-29T22:00:44.122514Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-29T22:00:44.132159Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-29T22:00:44.122484Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-29T22:00:44.131322Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"PRW root: /kaggle/input/datasets/edoardomerli/prw-person-re-identification-in-the-wild\nContents: ['ID_test.mat', 'ID_train.mat', 'annotations', 'frame_test.mat', 'frame_train.mat', 'frames', 'generate_query.m', 'query_box', 'query_info.txt', 'readme.txt']\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":4},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 2. Dataset: PRW\n\nThe PRW dataset (Zheng et al., CVPR 2017) contains 11,816 frames from 6 cameras with 43,110 annotated pedestrian bounding boxes. Of these, 34,304 are assigned to one of 932 identities, while the rest are labeled \"ambiguous\" (ID = -2). There are 2,057 query bounding boxes for evaluation.\n\n| Split | Frames | IDs | Total BBoxes | Labeled | Unlabeled |\n|-------|--------|-----|-------------|---------|-----------|\n| Train | 5,134  | 482 | 16,243      | 13,416  | 2,827     |\n| Val   | 570    | 482 | 1,805       | 1,491   | 314       |\n| Test  | 6,112  | 450 | 25,062      | 19,127  | 5,935     |\n\nA small number of IDs appear in both train and test frames, but the query IDs (the ones we evaluate on) are exclusive to the test set, so there is no identity leakage during evaluation.","metadata":{"_uuid":"46531dce-1de1-4cdb-ad4c-e535d45ce234","_cell_guid":"dc61ecb9-3695-484f-a4f0-db27e32ada0c","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"train_dataset = PRWGalleryDataset(DATASET_ROOT, split=\"train\")\nval_dataset   = PRWGalleryDataset(DATASET_ROOT, split=\"val\")\ntest_dataset  = PRWGalleryDataset(DATASET_ROOT, split=\"test\")\nquery_dataset = PRWQueryDataset(DATASET_ROOT)\n\nprint(f\"Train frames : {len(train_dataset):,}\")\nprint(f\"Val   frames : {len(val_dataset):,}\")\nprint(f\"Test  frames : {len(test_dataset):,}\")\nprint(f\"Queries      : {len(query_dataset):,}\")","metadata":{"_uuid":"48735f4f-9099-41be-b0b5-308fa6327371","_cell_guid":"56774745-d8d8-49a1-8779-bf0a0dc3e721","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false},"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-29T22:03:00.614296Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-29T22:03:00.614757Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-29T22:03:10.538873Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-29T22:03:00.614732Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-29T22:03:10.538040Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Train frames : 5,133\nVal   frames : 571\nTest  frames : 6,112\nQueries      : 2,057\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":10},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 3. Data Exploration\n\nBefore building the model, I inspect the data to understand its characteristics. Specifically: how often each identity appears (are some IDs rare?), the distribution of bounding box heights (what scale variation do we have?), and aspect ratios (are the boxes roughly consistent?). This is useful for sanity checking and can inform choices like anchor sizes.","metadata":{"_uuid":"83a3a0a3-7415-4f61-8638-06182fdb4358","_cell_guid":"a32c66d1-3969-4d59-85b1-b39da7034580","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"all_pids, all_widths, all_heights = [], [], []\nfor ann in train_dataset.annotations:\n    for b, p in zip(ann[\"boxes\"], ann[\"pids\"]):\n        if p > 0:\n            all_pids.append(p)\n            all_widths.append(b[2] - b[0])\n            all_heights.append(b[3] - b[1])\n\npid_counts = Counter(all_pids)\n\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 4))\n\naxes[0].hist(list(pid_counts.values()), bins=40, color=\"#4C72B0\", edgecolor=\"white\")\naxes[0].set_title(\"Appearances per Identity (Train)\")\naxes[0].set_xlabel(\"# appearances\")\naxes[0].set_ylabel(\"# identities\")\n\naxes[1].hist(all_heights, bins=50, color=\"#DD8452\", edgecolor=\"white\")\naxes[1].set_title(\"Bounding Box Heights (px)\")\naxes[1].set_xlabel(\"height (px)\")\n\nratios = np.array(all_heights) / np.array(all_widths)\naxes[2].hist(ratios, bins=50, color=\"#55A868\", edgecolor=\"white\")\naxes[2].set_title(\"Aspect Ratios (h/w)\")\naxes[2].set_xlabel(\"aspect ratio\")\n\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.savefig(\"eda_statistics.png\", dpi=120, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\nplt.show()\n\nprint(f\"Median box height:  {np.median(all_heights):.1f} px\")\nprint(f\"Median aspect ratio: {np.median(ratios):.2f}\")\nprint(f\"Unique train IDs:   {len(pid_counts)}\")","metadata":{"_uuid":"9a206969-72dc-4b68-be80-f7e474ef20bf","_cell_guid":"c0373677-b4a7-40b7-989c-378fd0fbe4e9","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false},"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-29T22:04:45.348017Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-29T22:04:45.348509Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-29T22:04:46.485158Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-29T22:04:45.348480Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-29T22:04:46.484432Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1500x400 with 3 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"name":"stdout","text":"Median box height:  62.0 px\nMedian aspect ratio: 0.16\nUnique train IDs:   583\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":11},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def show_scene(dataset, idx, title=\"\"):\n    ann = dataset.annotations[idx]\n    img = np.array(Image.open(\n        osp.join(dataset.img_prefix, ann[\"img_name\"])).convert(\"RGB\"))\n    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(12, 5))\n    ax.imshow(img)\n    cmap = plt.cm.get_cmap(\"tab20\", 30)\n    for box, pid in zip(ann[\"boxes\"], ann[\"pids\"]):\n        x1, y1, x2, y2 = box\n        color = cmap(pid % 20) if pid > 0 else \"gray\"\n        rect = patches.Rectangle((x1, y1), x2 - x1, y2 - y1,\n                                  linewidth=2, edgecolor=color, facecolor=\"none\")\n        ax.add_patch(rect)\n        lbl = str(pid) if pid > 0 else \"?\"\n        ax.text(x1, y1 - 4, lbl, color=color, fontsize=7,\n                fontweight=\"bold\", bbox=dict(fc=\"white\", alpha=0.4, pad=1))\n    ax.set_title(title or ann[\"img_name\"])\n    ax.axis(\"off\")\n    plt.tight_layout()\n    plt.show()\n\nfor i in [0, 50, 200]:\n    show_scene(train_dataset, i, title=f\"Train sample #{i}\")\n\n# query crops\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 8, figsize=(20, 5))\nfor i, ax in enumerate(axes):\n    ann = query_dataset.annotations[i]\n    img = Image.open(osp.join(query_dataset.query_dir, ann[\"img_name\"])).convert(\"RGB\")\n    ax.imshow(img)\n    ax.set_title(f\"PID {ann['pids']}\\nCam {ann['cam_id']}\", fontsize=9)\n    ax.axis(\"off\")\nplt.suptitle(\"Sample Query Crops\", fontsize=13, y=1.02)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.savefig(\"query_samples.png\", dpi=120, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\nplt.show()","metadata":{"_uuid":"f5bcf0f2-99ca-4fea-a21a-f50330b35f38","_cell_guid":"d313a0ca-a485-4eb2-8c17-cf127167a700","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false},"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-29T22:04:53.270092Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-29T22:04:53.271189Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-29T22:04:55.764143Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-29T22:04:53.271153Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-29T22:04:55.763248Z"},"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 2000x500 with 8 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":12},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 4. Model Architecture\n\nThe code for the model, loss functions, and evaluation is in separate Python scripts (`models.py`, `losses.py`, `eval_utils.py`) for readability and because the DDP training script (`train_ddp.py`) needs to import them too.\n\nThe architecture is a Faster R-CNN with an additional Re-ID branch:\n\n1. **Backbone (ResNet + FPN):** extracts multi-scale features from the input.\n2. **RPN:** generates region proposals likely to contain pedestrians.\n3. **RoI Align:** crops and resizes features per proposal into 7x7 maps.\n4. **Box Head (TwoMLPHead):** maps the pooled features to a 1024-d vector.\n5. **Detection Head:** classifies (person vs. background) and refines boxes.\n6. **Re-ID Head:** projects the same 1024-d vector to a 256-d L2-normalized embedding.\n\nDuring training, the joint loss is:\n\n$$\\mathcal{L} = \\mathcal{L}_{cls} + \\mathcal{L}_{reg} + \\lambda \\cdot \\mathcal{L}_{reid}$$\n\nwhere $\\mathcal{L}_{reid}$ is either OIM or triplet loss, and $\\lambda = 0.5$.\n\n**OIM loss** (Xiao et al., CVPR 2017) maintains a lookup table of identity prototypes updated via exponential moving average, plus a circular queue for unlabeled samples. Each embedding is compared to all entries via scaled cosine similarity. This lets the model see all 482 training identities at every step, regardless of batch composition, which is critical when batch sizes are small.\n\n**Triplet loss** (Hermans et al., 2017) uses batch-hard mining: for each anchor, it selects the hardest positive and hardest negative within the batch. The limitation is that with 2 images per GPU, only a few IDs are present per step.\n\nThe full model code is in `models.py`, losses in `losses.py`.","metadata":{"_uuid":"6eb738d5-2dc8-4df6-b1e0-483ea3cb4fe9","_cell_guid":"643904a0-a364-4a2a-a5b6-40cd5b9fff7f","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 5. Training with DDP\n\nTraining uses PyTorch's `DistributedDataParallel` across Kaggle's 2 T4 GPUs, launched via `torchrun`. The key differences from single-GPU training:\n\n- **Process spawning:** `torchrun` launches one process per GPU. Each process initializes its own model replica.\n- **DistributedSampler:** the dataset is automatically partitioned so each GPU sees a different subset of images per epoch. `sampler.set_epoch(epoch)` is called each epoch to reshuffle.\n- **Gradient synchronization:** DDP automatically averages gradients across GPUs after each backward pass, so the model parameters stay in sync.\n- **Logging:** only rank 0 prints, logs to wandb, and saves checkpoints, to avoid duplicate output.\n\nThe effective batch size is `batch_size_per_gpu * num_gpus`. With 2 images per GPU and 2 GPUs, the effective batch is 4, which is twice what a single T4 can handle.\n\nI train three variants:\n1. **Baseline:** ResNet-50 + OIM\n2. **Ablation A:** ResNet-18 + OIM (testing backbone depth)\n3. **Ablation B:** ResNet-50 + Triplet (testing loss function)\n\nAll training metrics are logged to Weights & Biases.","metadata":{"_uuid